<HEADLINE>
FORMER KMT ACTING HEAD REGISTERS FOR PARTY CHAIRMANSHIP
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taipei,  March 18 (CNA) 03/18/07  20:43:58 (By Luis Huang)
</P>
<P>
Opposition Kuomintang (KMT) former acting Chairman Wu Poh-hsiung
registered his candidacy for the party's top post Sunday at KMT
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
After completing his registration, Wu said, if elected, he will
do his utmost to promote party unity and select a KMT
presidential ticket capable of winning the 2008 presidential
election under the instructions of Honorary Chairman Lien Chan.
</P>
<P>
Wu also promised to continue to promote the KMT's internal
reforms, including the party's organizational structure and party
assets management.
</P>
<P>
In order to compete for the KMT's top post, Wu resigned his post
as acting chairman last week, with Vice Chairman P.K. Chiang
succeeding him as the party's acting chairman.
</P>
<P>
In addition to Wu, KMT Legislator Hung Hsiu-chun is also expected
to register for the chairmanship by-election, and party members
will elect a new leader in a direct vote April 7.
</P>
<P>
The by-election was made necessary by Ma's resignation as KMT
chairman Feb. 13 immediately after his indicted on corruption
charges for the alleged misuse of a special discretionary
allowance fund during his two terms as Taipei mayor from 1998 -
2006.  Ma simultaneously announced that he will run in the 2008
presidential election.
</P>
<P>
In addition to Ma, Legislative Yuan Speaker Wang Jin-pyng, a KMT
stalwart, is also considering throwing his hat into the ring to
vie for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
The KMT leadership has voiced its hope that Lien will mediate
among the party's presidential aspirants to help ensure that the
party fields only one presidential candidate.
</P>
